CLIENT-SERVER ARCHITECTURE (What happens when you run a container)

Docker command line sends request to daemon
Daemons passes req to containerd
Containerd prepares and manages the container then calls runc
runc creates container then it runs

*Docker daemon is the brain that receives req & interpret & forward to containerd(tells who what to do, delegate task)
Containerd prepares container environment, manage images and tells runc to start container
runc is the container creator (talks to linux kernel features like namespaces, cgroups to create an isolated process and start container)

*Docker does not create container alone, they are created by linux kernel feature triggered by runc

Dockerfile is the set of instructions/blueprint of a file that contains all instr. for an app

To containerize an app, write a dockerfile, which is used to build an image then the image is used to create and run containers.

Example:
If i run; docker run nginx on my CLI
Docker daemon receives my req and checks if image is available locally, if not;
It tells containerd to pull image from registry(docker hub)
Containerd connects to docker hub and pulls image from it then save it locally, prepares environment and tells runc to start container

docker run -it ubuntu (creates and starts a new Ubuntu container with an interactive terminal)
docker ps / docker container ls (to see all running container)
docker images (to check which images are running)
docker stop containerID (to stop container)
docker start containerID (to start container)
docker rm containerID (to remove a container that has stopped running)
docker inspect containerID (info about a container image)
docker logs containerID (check logs of a container)
docker container prune -f (deletes all stopped containers)
docker container -exec -it containerID bash (opens a bash shell inside an already running container)
To run an nginx web server on my computer at port 8080; docker run -d -p 8080:80 nginx
-t (tag) is used to give docker image a name

When the content of a container is edited and you want to save current state of container into new image is called docker commit
docker commit -m “added new file” containerID names_ubuntu (-m means note/message to read “added new file”, names_ubuntu is the new image name 
